You’ll find a live demo at the end of the article 😉
Simple use case: Celsius & Fahrenheit
Say we link a Celsius signal to a Fahrenheit signal. Whenever Celsius changes, Fahrenheit should update accordingly. So we use Celsius as the source signal and Fahrenheit as the linkedSignal that derives its value from it.
But what if the user sets Fahrenheit directly? That’s where the custom set shines. We intercept the write and update Celsius instead, so both stay in sync:
tempC = signal(0);
tempF = linkedSignal(() => (this.tempC() * 9) / 5 + 32, {
set: (valF) => {
return this.tempC.set(((valF - 32) * 5) / 9);
},
});Simply put: this feature lets you route updates back to the source of truth.
When tempC changes, tempF updates automatically — that's the normal linkedSignal behavior. But when you call tempF.set(212), instead of storing 212 directly in tempF, our custom set runs, updates tempC, and tempF recomputes from it. Both signals stay synchronized either way.
console.info(this.tempF()); // 32 = (0 * 9) / 5 + 32
this.tempF.set(212);
console.info(this.tempC()); // 100 = (212 - 32) * 5 / 9
console.info(this.tempF()); // 212To be clear about what’s happening:

• Reading tempF() always gives a derived value

• Writing tempF.set(212) does not store 212 inside tempF

• It updates tempC instead

• Then tempF recomputes from tempC
The custom set only runs when you manually call tempF.set(...). Angular takes care of the rest.

All good? Let’s look at a more advanced use case! 👇
Updating a nested property in a parent object
Imagine an order object with an id and a shippingMethod, and a separate signal that represents just the shipping method.
order is the source. shippingMethod is the linkedSignal that derives its value from order().shippingMethod. When order changes, shippingMethod stays in sync automatically.
Now imagine the user picks a new shipping method in the UI. That triggers shippingMethod.set(...). Without the new feature, shippingMethod would update but order.shippingMethod would be left out of sync. With a custom set, we intercept that write and patch the parent object too:
order = signal<Order>({ id: 42, shippingMethod: 'Ground' });
shippingMethod = linkedSignal(() => this.order().shippingMethod, {
set: (newMethod) => {
this.order.update((currentOrder) => ({
...currentOrder,
shippingMethod: newMethod,
}));
},
});Powerful, right? 😄
The linkedSignal acts as a focused lens into a nested property, reads derive from the parent, writes propagate back to it.
